{"date": "2018-09-12", "title": "Essay Writing Competition 2019", "content": "The Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce, wishes to inform of the opening of the Annual Essay Writing Competition 2018/2019.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \n\u00a0\nSOURCE:\u00a0 Ministry of Foreign Affairs", "id": "1965ff5fb0a83ebcbc28614a48efabdd"}
{"date": "2020-10-30", "title": "Saint Vincent and the Grenadines to Assume Presidency of the United Nations Security Council", "content": "On November 1st, 2020, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines (SVG), will assume the presidency of the United Nations Security Council (UNSC), for one month, ending November 30th, 2020. This is SVG\u2019s first and only presidency during the country\u2019s stint on the council, and forms part of its responsibility as a non-permanent member.\nSaint Vincent and the Grenadines\u2019 presidency, aims to address contemporary challenges, which include: Pandemics, Environmental Challenges, Climate Change and its Security Consequences, and the Nexus Between Development and Peace and Security.\nKey events for the month of November include:\n\nNovember 2nd, 2:00 p.m.: Press briefing \u2013 The briefing will be conducted by Hon. Dr. Ralph E. Gonsalves, Prime Minister of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, and will be streamed live from http://webtv.un.org/. The event will also be streamed live from the Facebook pages of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce, and the Permanent Mission of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines to the United Nations, and will be aired on the 'Eye on Government' programme hosted by the Agency for Public Information.\nNovember 3rd, 9:30 a.m.: (Signature event) \u2013 Security Council Virtual Open Debate under the agenda theme \u201cPeacebuilding and Sustainable Peace: Contemporary Drivers of Conflict and Insecurity\u201d. This high level Virtual Open Debate will be chaired by the Hon. Dr. Ralph E. Gonsalves, Prime Minister of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines. The event will be streamed live from http://webtv.un.org/. The event will also be streamed live from the Facebook pages of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce and the Permanent Mission of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines to the United Nations, and will be aired on the 'Eye on Government' programme hosted by the Agency for Public Information.\nNovember 4th: Meeting of the Police Commissioners of the UN Peacekeeping Missions; intended to highlight issues affecting Haiti.\nNovember 16th: Peace and security in Africa [G5 Sahel]\n\nSaint Vincent and the Grenadines was officially elected as a non-permanent member of the United Nations Security Council, and officially assumed its position on January 2, 2020, which runs for a period of two years; culminating on December 31, 2021.\n\u00a0\nSOURCE: Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce", "id": "1a5d315aeeac35ce9fbdbe589e0557b5"}
{"date": "2017-11-30", "title": "Mid-level Diplomat Course in New Delhi, India", "content": "The Ministry of External Affairs \u2013 Foreign Service Institute in New Delhi India hosted a special two-week course for diplomats from within the Caribbean Community (CARICOM). The course commenced on Monday 13th November and continued through to Friday 24th November.\nThe programme was in keeping with the vision of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce to nurture and develop a professional, innovative and responsive public service organization, which promotes an effective foreign and trade policy and a sustainable knowledge economy. \u00a0During the two-week period, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines was represented by Ms. Tamira Browne and Ms. Khalila Roache, from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce. There were 10 other CARICOM countries represented: Antigua and Barbuda, Bahamas, Barbados, Belize, Grenada, Guyana, Haiti, Saint Lucia, Saint Kitts and Nevis, and Suriname. Officials from the Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States and the Caribbean Community were also present to participate in the course. \u00a0The diplomats were exposed to various aspects of India\u2019s Foreign Policy, expertise on bilateral and multilateral arrangements and a range of institutions that support the fulfillment of foreign policy agendas. \u00a0The Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce will continue to work towards deepening and widening regional and international alliances to promote national interest.", "id": "1a875101675c3b0d80708a79ab738aa9"}
{"date": "2021-11-05", "title": "Her Excellency Dame Susan Dougan, Accepts Letters Of Credence From Switzerland Ambassador, H.E. J\u00fcrg Sprecher", "content": "On Wednesday, 3rd November, 2021, H.E. Mr. J\u00fcrg Sprecher presented Letters of Credence to Her Excellency Dame Susan Dougan, GCMG, OBE, Governor General of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines as the newly accredited non-resident Ambassador Extraordinary & Plenipotentiary of Switzerland to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines.\nAmbassador Sprecher holds a doctorate in political Science from the University of Basel, Switzerland. Prior to his current post, His Excellency held the posts of Deputy Head of Mission in Madrid, and Head of the Swiss Embassy in Caracas, Venezuela. Ambassador Sprecher is multilingual in speaking English, German, French and Spanish.\nThe Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade and by extension the Government of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines take this opportunity to welcome the newly appointed Ambassador and renew the Government\u2019s commitment in working together to strengthen the bilateral cooperation between both countries.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\nSOUCE: Ministry of foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade", "id": "1b0acbcbc31e3354978925325e988658"}
{"date": "2019-09-20", "title": "The Australian Government\u2019s Direct Aid Program (DAP) For 2019-2020", "content": "The Australian Government\u00a0 in conjunction with the Australian Government\u2019s Direct Aid Program (DAP) is offering small grants for various community and developmental projects to local Community groups and local government organizations, NGOs and other entities engaged in development activities on a not-for-profit basis in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines.\nSince 2005, the Australian Government has been supporting DAP projects in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines. DAP is a small grants program through which the Australian Government supports development projects that contribute to sustainable economic growth and poverty reduction.\u00a0\u00a0For the year 2019-2020 DAP will support local projects which focus on the following areas:\n\naddressing community health challenges and non-communicable diseases e.g. health screening service, public health campaigns, sporting projects;\n\n\npromoting human rights including projects that empower women, youth, indigenous communities and people with disability, e.g. capacity building training;\n\n\nimproving access to safer water and levels of sanitation and hygiene in communities e.g. water tanks/systems, sanitation facilities; and\n\n\npromoting sustainable environmental practices e.g. protection of coral reefs, sustainable fishing and sustainable agricultural practices.\n\nFor more information on the DAP application process and requirements, interested groups can visit the Australian High Commission\u2019s website at:\u00a0https://trinidadandtobago.highcommission.gov.au/ptsp/cooperation.html.The first round of DAP applications for\u00a02019-2020 was opened on September 14th, 2019, with a closing date of October 20th, 2019.The second round of DAP applications\u00a0is scheduled to be opened on December 7th, 2019 and closes on 12th January, 2020.\nSOURCE: API", "id": "1bb6067cca953d01b4d3b44f89438d93"}
{"date": "2023-01-26", "title": "SVG is the First CARICOM Country to Assume the Presidency of CELAC", "content": "Having achieved unanimous support, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines is now the first CARICOM country to assume the Pro Tempore Presidency of the Community of Latin American and the Caribbean States (CELAC) for the period 2023.\n\nAt the Seventh Summit of Heads of State and Government convened in Buenos Aires, Argentina on 24th January 2023, the thirty-three (33) member organisation consented to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines being the Pro Tempore President for one year.\n\nDuring the Summit, member states committed to several declarations that will guide the Community\u2019s agenda and policies including special declarations on gender equality, food systems, and ocean conservation and on the need to put an end to blockade on Cuba.\n\nSaint Vincent and the Grenadines\u2019 delegation was headed by Dr. the Honourable Ralph Gonsalves; Prime Minister, and included Senator the Honourable Keisal Peters; Minister Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade, His Excellency Gareth Bynoe; Ambassador for Saint Vincent and the Grenadines-Resident in the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela, and His Excellency Ambassador Andreas Wickham.", "id": "1c1e606222bd3f5aa90094fd9e325038"}
{"date": "2021-10-28", "title": "The Government Of Saint Vincent And The Grenadines Joins In United Nations Day Celebrations", "content": "The Government of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, collaborates with the United Nations Barbados and Eastern Caribbean, in celebration of United Nations (UN), Day, which is observed annually on October 24th.\u00a0 UN Day has been celebrated since 1948 and marks the anniversary of the entry into force of the UN Charter in 1945.\nTo commemorate the UN\u2019s 76th milestone, and to symbolize the ongoing partnership between Saint Vincent and the Grenadines and the UN, the Government is co-ordinating two events as follows:\n\nA\u00a0 Flag Raising Ceremony to commence at 8:30 a.m. instead of 9:00 a.m. on Friday, 29th October, 2021, at the Financial Complex, Kingstown. \nA tree planting ceremony to highlight Action on Climate, and the upcoming COP26 at the Rabacca Village to be held also on Friday,\u00a0 29th October at 11:30 a.m.\u00a0 The Tree planting will be done by Hon. Saboto Caesar, Minister of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries.\n\nBoth events will be attended by Senior Government officials as well as UN representatives. The Honourable Prime Minister, Dr. Ralph Gonsalves, and UN Resident Coordinator, Didier Trebucq, will deliver remarks at the Flag raising ceremony, which also marks our 41st anniversary of membership in the UN, having joined on 16th September 1980.The flag-raising ceremony will be livestreamed via VC3, and members of the public are invited to view the event live on VC3 Facebook page: @vincycultureconnectionchannel or via the VC3 local TV Channel or\u00a0 its YouTube channel at:\u00a0 VC3TV.UN Day will also be observed in Barbados and across select OECS countries.For further information, please contact the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade at telephone number 456 2060.", "id": "1d19701144a732a5aeb003d592062f9b"}
{"date": "2020-02-12", "title": "Advancement of SVG \u2013 Ghana Relations", "content": "A delegation led by Honourable Sir Louis Straker; Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of\u00a0Foreign Affairs, met with senior officials from the Government of the Republic of Ghana for the 5th preparatory meeting towards the First Session of the Saint Vincent and the Grenadines-Ghana Permanent Joint Commission for Cooperation (PJCC), at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Regional Integration in Accra, Ghana.\n\nHonourable Saboto Caesar, Minister of Agriculture, Forestry, Fisheries, Rural Transformation, Industry and Labour, presented on issues and areas for cooperation in root crop production, fisheries, cocoa technology, breadfruit and ackee. The Honourable Minister explained that with Saint Vincent and the Grenadines cementing itself as the bread basket of the Southern Caribbean, there must be deepening of the diversification process. He added that, \u201cwe must ensure that when it comes to food, SVG must be the country where you can get the supply of the widest variety of commodities\u201d.\nHis Excellency Ambassador Ellsworth John; Non-Resident Ambassador of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines to the Republic of Ghana-Designate, and Mrs. Sandy Peters-Phillips; Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce, presented on the ABCD Commission for the advancement of trading opportunities and people to people exchanges.\n\nThe delegation participated in the signing of a Memorandum of Understanding on Tuesday 11th February, 2020 between both states at the First Session of the Saint Vincent and the Grenadines-Ghana Permanent Joint Commission for Cooperation. At the Session, opportunities for tourism, culture, investment, trade, agriculture and youth development were discussed.\nThe official visit to Ghana commenced on Monday 10th February, and will end on Friday 14th February, 2020.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0SOURCE: Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce", "id": "1d84b01f61423487b350bf28ada9ee88"}
{"date": "2022-12-30", "title": "Ambassador Of The People's Democratic Republic Of Algeria Presents Letters Of Credence To The Governor General Of SVG", "content": "Newly accredited Non-Resident Ambassador of the People\u2019s Democratic Republic of Algeria to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, His Excellency Abdelkader Hadjazi presented Letters of Credence to Her Excellency, Dame Susan Dougan, GCMG, OBE at Government House, Kingstown on Friday, 16th December, 2022.\nPlease click for full details.", "id": "1d9e5a42afa33beeafb86e7f03751726"}
{"date": "2022-01-24", "title": "Ministerial Meeting On Haiti", "content": "On January 21, 2022, an international ministerial-level meeting on Haiti was held at the invitation of the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Canada, and under that country\u2019s Chairmanship.\nAmong the invitees to this meeting were CARICOM\u2019s Secretary General, Dr. Carla Barnett, and the Prime Minister of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, Dr. The Hon. Ralph E. Gonsalves. The list of speakers at the meeting is attached hereto.\nThe interventions of the Secretary General of CARICOM and the Prime Minister of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines at this meeting are attached also. So, too, are two other contributions from Prime Minister Ralph Gonsalves:\n\n\u201cNotes on the Way Forward for Haiti (Ideas Towards a CARICOM Position)\u201d submitted to CARICOM on July 19, 2021;\nRemarks at the United Nations Security Council on Haiti on October 15, 2021.\n\nIn our Caribbean we owe Haiti a debt of gratitude; solidarity with Haiti is our solemn obligation. We must be informed on Haiti and stay engaged.\nAttachments\n\nSpeakers List - Agenda - Ministerial Meeting on Haiti\nRevised - Notes on the Way Forward for Haiti\nRemarks by CARICOM SG Ministerial Meeting on Haiti\nRemarks by PM of SVG - International Ministerial Meeting on Haiti\nStatement by PM SVG on Haiti - Arria Formula\n\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\nSOURCE:\u00a0Office of the Prime Minister", "id": "1f69979e0583336abdb68778bd776d96"}
{"date": "2022-03-08", "title": "Women's Day Address by The Hon. Keisal Peters", "content": "The Republic of China (Taiwan) recently provided support to the Government of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines by offering opportunity for entrepreneurial training and grant assistance to Vincentian women in business through the Women's Empowerment Project which is being collaborated between the Embassy of the Republic of China (Taiwan) in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines and the Centre for Enterprise Development.\nToday on International Women's Day, the Ministry is pleased to share the below video message from Senator The Hon. Keisal Peters, Minister of State with Responsibility for Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade.\n\u00a0\n\nSOURCE: Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade", "id": "1f88375ef9d13e0ea08d9ba6b08b4395"}
{"date": "2015-04-29", "title": "Venezuela's Miracle Mission", "content": "A group of medical professionals from the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela recently visited St. Vincent and the Grenadines as part of the Governments\u2019 mission to promote and protect the well-being of its citizens.\nThe group made visits to several health care centres across the country to carry out assessments and pre-selected persons to travel to Venezuela for further medical eye care and surgery.\u00a0\u00a0 Persons affected by pathologies or eye conditions related to ophthalmology such as cataract and pterygium fleshiness (which is a growth of pink, fleshy tissue on the white of the eye), were particularly selected.The experts visit was a fulfillment of an agreement signed between the Government of St. Vincent and the Grenadines and the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela to implement a vision care program titled Miracle Vision across the island.", "id": "1fc56177878a319fbcfbe3faaadb615d"}
{"date": "2022-07-28", "title": "His Excellency Gareth Bynoe, Ambassador of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines to the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela Presented Letters of Credence", "content": "The Ministry takes this opportunity to inform that His Excellency Gareth Bynoe, Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines to the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela in Caracas, presented his Letter of Credence to His Excellency Nicol\u00e1s Maduro, President of the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela on Monday July 25, 2022, thus completing the process of accreditation in the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela.\nClick for more information.\n\u00a0\n\nHis Excellency, Ambassador Gareth Bynoe meeting His Excellency, Nicol\u00e1s Maduro, President ofthe Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela to present his Letters of Credence.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\nHis Excellency, Nicol\u00e1s Maduro, President of the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela accepted Lettersof Credence from His Excellency Ambassador Gareth Bynoe.\n\u00a0\n\nAmbassador Bynoe greeted with a welcome parade prior to presentation of His Letters of Credence.\n\u00a0\n\nOn Monday July 18, 2022, His Excellency Gareth Bynoe, Ambassador of Saint Vincent and theGrenadines to the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela presented a Style Copy of his Letter ofCredence to His Excellency Carlos Faria, Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Bolivarian Republic ofVenezuela.\n\u00a0\nSOURCE: Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade", "id": "20394284519730829206b647f3e58cd0"}
{"date": "2023-04-26", "title": "H.E. Ms. Beate Stir\u2205, Ambassador of the Kingdom of Norway, Presented Letters of Credence to the Governor General of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines", "content": "H.E. Beate Stir\u00f8, Ambassador of the Kingdom of Norway, presented Letters of Credence to H.E. Dame Susan Dougan, GCMG, OBE, Governor General of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines at Government House on Friday, April 21st, 2023.\n\nAmbassador Stir\u00f8 also met with Dr. The Hon. Ralph E. Gonsalves; Prime Minister, Hon. Godwin Friday; Leader of the Opposition as well as other high-level officials from the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry, Fisheries, Rural Transformation, Industry and Labour on Friday, April 21st, 2023.\n\nThe Governments of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines and The Kingdom of Norway established diplomatic ties on February 19th, 1993 and have enjoyed fruitful relations over the years.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\nSOURCE:\u00a0Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade", "id": "23944bc3c9c0366e8b0c6e9e2b381add"}
{"date": "2019-12-16", "title": "Commencement of the Recruitment of Nurses from SVG to the United Kingdom \u2013 January 2020", "content": "The Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce is pleased to inform that recruiters from Global Learners Programme of Health Education England will return to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines in January, 2020, to conduct the second phase of recruitment of registered nurses from Saint Vincent and the Grenadines to the United Kingdom.\nAll interested persons are asked to submit a Curriculum Vitae (CV) and a copy of a valid nursing license to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce by December 20th, 2019. Please be advised that only twenty five (25) slots remain available.\nFor further information, please contact the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce at telephone number: 456 2067.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\nSOURCE: Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce", "id": "239732c8925b3eb69b65ff4de7fd8cee"}
{"date": "2023-01-04", "title": "Canada provides $74,000 to two NGOs in SVG through the Canada Fund for Local Initiatives", "content": "The High Commission of Canada is pleased to contribute more than CAD74,000 in funding to two non-governmental organizations in St. Vincent and the Grenadines, through the Canada Fund for Local Initiatives (CFLI).\nPlease click for more details", "id": "25253c280e7633d58c77ae988ab9af9b"}
{"date": "2022-03-02", "title": "Letter to President of Russia", "content": "As a longstanding friend of the Russian Federation, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines is deeply disturbed at your government\u2019s initiative of a \u201cspecial military operation\u201d in the territory of Ukraine, an independent republic. Please click for full details.", "id": "2556646ca69e3f5f8a44c4ea2ac27214"}
{"date": "2023-01-31", "title": "CELAC Summit in Buenos Aires", "content": "The President of the European Council, Charles Michel and the Prime Minister of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, Ralph Gonsalves...\nannounced that the next EU-CELAC Summit of Heads of State and Government will take place in Brussels on July 17th and 18th, when Spain holds the rotating Presidency of the Council of the European Union.\nPresident Michel congratulated Prime Minister Gonsalves on the assumption of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines as the new protempore presidency of CELAC.\nThe EU-CELAC Summit will further strengthen the bi-regional partnership of the EU and the CELAC countries on shared priorities like digital and green transitions, the fight against climate change and biodiversity loss, health, food security, migration, security and governance or the fight against transnational crime.\nThe President and the Prime Minister congratulated the President of Argentina, Alberto Fern\u00e1ndez on his successful pro tempore presidency of CELAC.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\nSOURCE:\u00a0Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade", "id": "25b9f75837eb3ec8926b341ded210166"}
{"date": "2019-11-08", "title": "Korean Film Night at the Russell's Cinema, Kingstown", "content": "The 28th of October, 2019, commemorated forty (40) years since this country established formal diplomatic relations with the Republic of South Korea.\nThroughout the years, both countries have solidified relations based on mutual understanding built on trust and respect for the joint benefit of our people in areas of common interest namely in agriculture, health, education, social development, people-to-people exchanges, infrastructure and sharing of unique cultures.\nThis year, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines was exposed to the Korean Culture through the \u201cSoul Beat\u201d programme at the SVG Community College to honour the forty (40) years of diplomatic relations with Saint Vincent and the Grenadines. The Embassy of the Republic of Korea will continue to share their culture with this country through a cultural event with the screening of two (2) Korean Films under the theme \u201cKorean Film Night\u201d. The cultural event will take place on Saturday, 23rd November, 2019, from 5:00 p.m. at the Russell\u2019s Cinema, Kingstown.\nThe Admission is free and on a first come, first served basis. Tickets will be distributed at the Russell\u2019s Cinema Box Office from 15th November, 2019. Only two (2) tickets will be allowed for each person.\n\u00a0\n\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\nSOURCE: Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce", "id": "27a0ee168f873b73a452a39417a431a0"}
{"date": "2016-06-21", "title": "Japan's Grant Assistance", "content": "The Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade Commerce and Regional Integration, is pleased to inform the nation of Japan\u2019s Grant Assistance for Grassroots Human Security Projects which offers funds to support developmental projects. \n\u00a0\nThe Government of Japan, through its Embassy in Trinidad and Tobago, is currently accepting applications under the GPP for the fiscal year 2016. The GPP is a financial assistance scheme for development projects. The scheme supports projects proposed by non-profit organisations, schools, hospitals and local government authorities, designed to benefit communities at the grassroots level. The ceiling for one project is US$83,333 for the fiscal year 2016.\n\u00a0\nEligible project areas\nProjects eligible under the scheme include, but are not limited to, poverty alleviation, public welfare, environmental protection and disaster risk reduction management, waste management, primary health care and education as follows:\n\u00a0\nEducation\n\nConstruction or renovation of classrooms in elementary and secondary education and technical-vocational courses.\n\n\u00a0\nSocial Welfare\n\nConstruction or improvement of centers, workshops or shelters for the marginalised sectors (children, elderly, indigenous people, persons with disabilities, women, etc.)\n\n\u00a0\nHealth and Sanitation\n\nUpgrading of health services in poor and remote areas through construction or improvement of health facilities and procurement of basic medical equipment in hospitals, rural health units and barangay health stations.\n\n\u00a0\nHow to apply\nCommunity groups and Non-Governmental Oganisations are encouraged to submit project applications to the Embassy of Japan in Trinidad and Tobago. Application forms are available at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade, Commerce and Regional Integration and can be downloaded from the following website http://www.tt.emb-japan.go.jp/grant%20assistance%20for%20ggp.htm\n\u00a0\nGroups can also contact the Embassy of Japan directly via the details below for more information:\nThe Embassy of Japan in Trinidad and Tobago\nOpening Hours: Monday to Friday, except office holidays, 08:00 \u00a0- 12:00, 13:00 - 16:30 hours.\nAddress: C/o Embassy of Japan in Trinidad and Tobago, 5 Hayes Street, St. Clair, Port of SpainP.O. Box 1039, Trinidad and Tobago\nTelephone: +1 868 628 5991E-mail: This email address is being protected from spambots. You need JavaScript enabled to view it.Website: http://www.tt.emb-japan.go.jp/grant%20assistance%20for%20ggp.htm \n\u00a0\nIt should be noted that there is no specific deadline for submitting applications. Applications are accepted all year round, however early applications are strongly encouraged.\n\u00a0\nSource: Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade, Commerce and Regional Integration", "id": "27fce0cc25d7309a9b6802f8224e4da8"}
{"date": "2018-08-02", "title": "Appointment of Honorary Consul", "content": "The Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce takes this opportunity to announce the decision to appoint Mr. Nigel R. Russell as the Honorary Consul of The Cooperative Republic of Guyana to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines.\nRead more", "id": "281d155878f13a739234cf8ab7770e7f"}
{"date": "2017-01-25", "title": "Qualified Vincentians Invited to Apply for Taiwanese FET Programme", "content": "The Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce is pleased to invite qualified unemployed Vincentian Nationals to apply for the Foreign English Teacher\u2019s (FET) Programme with the Ministry of Education of the Republic of China (Taiwan).\n\u00a0\nUnder the Foreign English Teacher\u2019s (FET) Programme, participants are invited to live and work in Taiwan as English Teachers for a period of one (1) year, with the possibility of having their contract renewed. To be eligible, applicants must possess either:\n\nAn Undergraduate degree,\nA Master\u2019s degree, or\nA Doctoral degree.\n\nAll candidates must possess a Teacher\u2019s Certificate. Retired English teachers are also welcome to apply.\n\u00a0\nFor further information, please contact the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, 3rd Floor Administrative Centre at telephone number 456-2060.\n\u00a0\nSOURCE: Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce", "id": "287d52d17fc53cd78548a952ce0f940e"}
