{"date": "2019-04-23", "title": "Police Recruits Receive Training in Protocol Procedures", "content": "The Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce conducted a one (1) day Protocol Training for Police Recruits on Friday, April 12, 2019, at the Old Montrose Police Station. The training was facilitated by Ms. Glenda Abraham, Foreign Service Officer attached to Protocol/Consular Division.\n\n\u00a0\nA total of seventy-nine (79) Recruits participated in the training. The Recruits were given an informative, interactive presentation to demonstrate the importance of protocol procedures in diplomacy, international relations and local interactions with people. The Ministry have seen this type of training as a vital tool for the Police Recruits that can be tremendously beneficial throughout their professional careers. The training will equip the Recruits with the right knowledge in understanding the ceremonial rules governing protocol for different functions, countries and welcoming diplomats.\nSo far, the Ministry have conducted protocol training with officials from the Ministry of Education, Youth & Sports, the Immigration Department, the SVG Police Force and several other private sectors such as the Seventh Day Adventist Church.\nThe Ministry will be extending this type of training to other line Ministries and critical Departments during the months of May to June, 2019.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\nSource: Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce", "id": "e2acfde927873f94bb7d3b32effb47f3"}
{"date": "2021-07-15", "title": "La Soufrierre Features Again In OAS Meeting", "content": "Ms. Michelle Forbes, Director of the National Management Organization (NEMO), gave an overview of the aftermath of the 2021 La Soufriere volcanic eruptions at the annual meeting on the Special Security Concerns of Small Island.\nPlease click for more information", "id": "e361f8600c0338f79990a1149a4ee80e"}
{"date": "2022-02-21", "title": "Government of Mexico Donates Astrzeneca Vaccines to the People of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines", "content": "On Friday, February 18th, 2022, a Mexican aircraft landed at the Argyle International Airport carrying ten thousand (10,000) doses of the Aztrazeneca vaccine to donate to the Government and People of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines\u00a0 from the Government of Mexico to help fight the COVID-19 pandemic.\u00a0\nPlease click for more details.", "id": "e3b4529b999f30ac9eba208ad1a2f223"}
{"date": "2020-03-06", "title": "Vincentians in the United Kingdom Donates to SVG Schools of Children with Special Needs", "content": "The SVG Vincentian Diaspora in the United Kingdom continues its efforts in giving back through its generous donation to assist the education system of this country.\n\nHon. Sir Louis Straker, H.E. Cenio Lewis, PS, Sandy Peters-Phillips, Mr. Dudrey Browne, SVG Reading Association and Mr. Denzil Winsborrow, New London Association\nIn a short ceremony held at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce on Tuesday, March 5th\u00a02020, the Saint Vincent and the Grenadines and Friends Association (Reading), England, and the Saint Vincent and the Grenadines New London Association donated a combined sum of EC$6,825.00 to the three Schools for Children With Special Needs in SVG. The SVG Reading Association donated EC$3,150.00; while SVG New London Association donated EC$3,675.00.\nMs. Michelle Stowe, Headteacher, received the donation on behalf of the Bequia Sunshine School for Children with Special Needs. Teacher, Ms. Sattra Phillips, collected the donation on behalf of the School with Special Needs, Georgetown; while Ms. Nassem Smith, Headteacher, received the donation on behalf of the School of Children with Special Needs, Kingstown.\nDuring the ceremony, Hon. Sir Louis Straker, Minister of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce highlighted the very important work that is being done through the SVG, High Commission London under the auspices H.E. Cenio Lewis and his staff; especially in collaboration with the Vincentian Diaspora in the UK. Minister Straker expressed gratitude to Mr. Dudrey Browne, Vice Chair of the SVG and Friends Association, UK and Mr. Denzil Winsborrow, Chairman, New London Association, UK, for the donation who both handed over the donation to the schools.\n\nMr. Denzil Winsborrow and H.E. Cenio Lewis in discussion with representatives form the Schools of Children with Special Needs\nH.E. Cenio Lewis also gave brief remarks and expressed that the donation, though it may seem infinitesimal, he would like the public to understand that the principle behind the donation is of utmost importance. The principle of giving back to your country, especially to the needs of the most vulnerable. High Commissioner Lewis emphasized that in the future when funds are collected from the Associations to be distributed to schools in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, that donation will be distributed to the School of Children with Special needs along with other schools in the country.\nThe donation to the Schools of Children With Special Needs would be used to purchase several items to assist the children\u2019s education development. These include textbooks and teaching aids for Bequia; materials for an Art Project and multi-sensory equipment for Kingstown; and garden tools, fabric, crayons and playground equipment for Georgetown.\nThe Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce and the Government of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, expressed gratitude to the SVG and Friends Association (Reading), England and the SVG New London Association for their continuous efforts in contributing to the economic development of this country be it healthcare, education or otherwise.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\nSOURCE: Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce", "id": "e69bb29fd5ab38adb8aac22b8714fc23"}
{"date": "2019-12-16", "title": "Thirty Four Public Servants Graduate From Spanish Speaking Training Programme", "content": "The Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce in collaboration with the Government of the Republic of Columbia held a graduation ceremony at the Ministry\u2019s conference room on December 11th, 2019.\nThe ceremony was to recognize the 34 public servants who participated in a training programme entitled \u201cDissemination of the Colombian culture through the teaching of Spanish as a foreign language\u201d offered through the University of Pontificia Bolivariana, of the Republic of Columbia.\nRemarks were delivered by Mr. Bernard John, Training Officer of the Services Commissions Department and Professor Jose Orlando Gomez Salazar. During his remarks, Hon. Sir Louis Straker, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce thanked Professor Salazar, the Service Commissions Department and all those entities that played their role in making the initiative a success. Hon. Minister Straker expressed special thanks to the Government of Columbia for expanding the people-to-people exchanges in further strengthening the diplomatic ties between both countries. Sir Louis also expressed the importance of connectivity and communication, which are two important elements in travelling and enhancing career opportunities. He therefore encouraged the students to know that being bilingual is an important tool that is marketable for today\u2019s working environment and thus, encouraged the students to continue in the next round in order to sharpen their Spanish speaking skills.\nThe 3-month training programme was held from September to December, 2019 and exposed the public servants to not only learning to write, read and speak Spanish but afforded them the opportunity to be exposed to the people and culture of Columbia. Cohort 1 of the speaking Spanish programme was conducted by Professor Jose Orlando Gomez Salazar from the University of Pontificia Bolivariana. Cohort 2 is expected to continue in the new year.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\nSOURCE:\u00a0\u00a0Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Trade and Commerce", "id": "e93479ecbcc53c55badb43619b6bb38e"}
{"date": "2014-11-07", "title": "New Resident Ambassador of The Republic of China (Taiwan) to SVG present his Letter of Credence", "content": "The new Resident Ambassador of the Republic of China (Taiwan) to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, His Excellency Bau-Shuan Ger, formally presented his Letter of Credence to His Excellency Sir Frederick Ballantyne, Governor General of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, on Friday August 3, 2014.\nAmbassador Ger who arrived in the State on September 12, 2014 is a career diplomat with years of experience having served in various top positions in the Republic of China (Taiwan)\u2019s Foreign Ministry. Before assuming the position as ambassador to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines he was Consul General to Chicago, in the State of Illinois, United States.\u00a0 While presenting his Letter of Credence to the Governor General, Ambassador Ger spoke highly of the warmth of Vincentians and the beauty of the country. He also expressed on behalf of his country, Taiwan\u2019s interest in continuing the longstanding fruitful relations between both countries. Saint Vincent and the Grenadines and the Republic of China (Taiwan) established diplomatic relations on the August 15, 1981. Both countries over the years have shared very close relations. Taiwan has contributed to the enhancement of various sectors in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, namely in the areas of Agriculture, Health, Social Development, Education and Infrastructure.", "id": "ebec91570ac031a5847bc8c9043ddfaa"}
{"date": "2022-06-28", "title": "H.E. Matsubara Yutaka, Ambassador of Japan to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines Presents Letters of Credence to the Governor General of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines", "content": "H.E. Matsubara Yutaka,Non-Resident Ambassador of Japan to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines presented Letters of Credence to H.E. Dame Susan Dougan, GCMG, OBE, Governor General of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines at the Government House on Monday June 27, 2022.\n\nNon-Resident Ambassador of Japan to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines presented Letters of Credence to H.E. Dame Susan Dougan, GCMG, OBE, Governor General of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines at the Government House on Monday, June 27, 2022.\nDuring his two-day visit to the State, Ambassador Yukata on Monday June 27 held bilateral discussions with Dr. The Hon. Ralph E. Gonsalves, Prime Minister and Senator The Hon. Keisal Peters, Minister of State with Responsibility for Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade reaffirming the strong bonds of friendship and cooperation between both countries. Further, the Prime Minister and Ambassador discussed the ongoing projects in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines being supported through Japan\u2019s assistance, and the prospects for future projects.\n\\\nNon-Resident Ambassador of Japan, H.E. Matsubara Yukata having bilateral discussion with Prime Minister of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines on Monday, June 27, 2022.\nPrime Minister Gonsalves also took the opportunity to congratulate Japan on its election as a Non-permanent Member on the United Nations Security Council and, reaffirmed Saint Vincent and the Grenadines\u2019 support towards Japan\u2019s tenure on the UNSC. Ambassador Yutaka also paid courtesy call on Hon. Montgomery Daniel, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Transport, Works, Lands and Physical Planning, Dr. The Hon. Godwin Friday, Leader of the Opposition, the Hon. Rochelle Forde, Speaker of the House of Assembly and H.E. Mr. Jos\u00e9 Manuel Leyva Ventura, Ambassador of the Republic of Cuba and Dean of the Diplomatic Corps.\nAmbassador Yutaka is an experienced public servant who served extensively within the Japanese Government service, holding three (3) master\u2019s degree in Civil Engineering; Urban and Regional Planning; and, Sea-use Law, Economics and Policies. Ambassador Yutaka is Resident in the Republic of Trinidad and Tobago with concurrent accreditation to other Caribbean Countries including Antigua and Barbuda, Dominica, Grenada, Guyana, St. Kitts and Nevis, St. Lucia and Suriname.\n\nNon-Resident Ambassador of Japan, H.E. Matsubara Yukata, Prime Minister, Dr. The Hon. Ralph E. Gonsalves and Minister of State with Responsibility for Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade, the Senator The Hon. Keisal M. Peters.\nThe Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade welcomes Ambassador Yutaka and looks forward to further deepening the relations between the Governments and People of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines and Japan. As part of the deepening of relations between both countries, Her Excellency, Andrea Bowman, Ambassador of SVG in Taiwan, will present Letters of Credence to the Emperor of Japan as a Non-Resident Ambassador by August 2022.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\n\u00a0\nSOURCE: Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade", "id": "ecb14e1afe1737468f817677ece41a84"}
